  help_driver_tasks: { id: "help_driver_tasks", label: "Driver Tasks — Internal One-Off Work", category: "operations", shortDescription: "How Driver Tasks differ from customer rental jobs, and where to create them.", guideDescription: "Driver Tasks are internal one-off operational items — 'bring the truck to Smith Auto Repair', 'swing by the recycling facility', 'yard errand', 'pick up parts at NAPA'. They are NOT customer rental jobs. Customer work always lives as a lifecycle job (delivery, exchange, pickup) attached to a customer, a rental chain, and billing. Driver Tasks have none of those — no customer, no chain, no price, no invoice. Create a Driver Task from the Dispatch top bar by clicking the New Task button next to Optimize Routes. The create drawer asks for a title (e.g. 'Bring truck to Smith Auto Repair'), the assigned driver, the scheduled date, an optional address, and optional notes. Once created, the task appears on the dispatch board and the driver's route for the selected day, visually distinct from customer jobs with a teal 'T' badge instead of the delivery/pickup/exchange colors. Driver Tasks do not appear on the Rental Lifecycles page, do not appear on the customer detail Jobs tab, do not appear in rental chains, and do not affect billing, pricing, or lifecycle status. They can be marked complete from the driver app the same way any job is completed. Under the hood Driver Tasks reuse the jobs table with `job_type = 'driver_task'` (same precedent as `dump_run`), so the existing dispatch, routing, and completion workflows work without new scaffolding. See the `JobsService.createDriverTask` backend method for implementation details.", routeOrSurface: "/dispatch", tenantOverrideKey: "help_driver_tasks", isUserFacing: true, isGuideEligible: true, keywords: ["task", "driver", "internal", "operational", "dispatch", "help"] },
