  lifecycle_performance: { id: "lifecycle_performance", label: "Lifecycle Performance", category: "operations", shortDescription: "Per-chain sortable performance table.", guideDescription: "", routeOrSurface: "/reports/lifecycle", tenantOverrideKey: "lifecycle_performance", isUserFacing: true, isGuideEligible: false, keywords: ["lifecycle", "performance"] },
  help_lifecycle_reporting: { id: "help_lifecycle_reporting", label: "Lifecycle Reporting & KPIs", category: "operations", shortDescription: "How the lifecycle report computes revenue, cost, profit, and overdue.", guideDescription: "Lifecycle Reporting is the rental-level view of your business. Unlike the task-level analytics page (which sums invoices and job costs at the tenant level), this report groups everything by rental chain — one row per rental, not one row per delivery/pickup/exchange. A rental is the unit of measurement: when a customer books a 20-yard dumpster, that's one chain that might include a delivery, an exchange, and a pickup. This page shows you the revenue, cost, profit, duration, and exchange count for each chain in one place.\n\n**What the KPIs measure.** Total Revenue sums `invoices.total` for every non-voided invoice linked to a chain in the date window via `invoices.rental_chain_id`. Total Cost sums `job_costs.amount` for every cost record attached to a job that belongs to a chain in the window, joined through `task_chain_links`. Total Profit is revenue minus cost — it's never stored, always derived, so there's no drift between the report and the lifecycle detail page. Average Rental Duration is the mean of `actual_pickup_date - drop_off_date` in days, calculated only on completed chains so active rentals don't skew the average. Active Rentals is the count of chains in the window whose status is `active`. Overdue Rentals is the subset of active chains whose `expected_pickup_date` is in the past — the chain is still active but the pickup never happened. Completed Rentals is chains whose status is `completed` in the window. Exchange Rate is the percentage of chains that have at least one non-cancelled exchange task — a useful proxy for how often customers need mid-rental swaps. Revenue per Chain and Profit per Chain are simple averages across the chains in the window.\n\n**Why there's a separate Standalone Jobs metric.** Jobs that aren't linked to any rental chain (legacy data, imports, manually-created pickups without a delivery) are excluded from every KPI above because they don't belong to a lifecycle. The Standalone Jobs widget at the bottom of the page is a cleanup metric — it links to the Phase 12 Legacy Backfill page where the owner can review those jobs and link them into chains. This is intentional separation: mixing standalone job revenue into lifecycle metrics would create misleading averages.\n\n**Why overdue is a point-in-time count.** Overdue compares `expected_pickup_date` to the current date, not to any date in the window. So a chain that dropped off inside the window but hasn't been picked up by today shows as overdue even if the window is backward-looking. This matches operator expectations: 'show me everything that's late right now'.\n\n**How the trend chart handles gaps.** The trend series is built by walking every bucket between the start and end dates at the selected granularity (day / week / month) and emitting a row for each — even if no chains dropped off in that bucket. Empty buckets show as zero, so the line chart is continuous with no visual gaps.\n\n**Financial consistency.** The financial math here is the exact same SQL used by `RentalChainsService.getFinancials` which powers the lifecycle detail page. Clicking a row in the performance table takes you to `/rentals/{chain_id}` where the same numbers will be shown — one source of truth, two views.", routeOrSurface: "/reports/lifecycle", tenantOverrideKey: "help_lifecycle_reporting", isUserFacing: true, isGuideEligible: true, keywords: ["lifecycle", "reporting", "kpi", "help"] },
