  chains_approved: { id: "chains_approved", label: "Chains Approved", category: "operations", shortDescription: "Number of chains approved this session.", guideDescription: "", routeOrSurface: "/admin/legacy-backfill", tenantOverrideKey: "chains_approved", isUserFacing: true, isGuideEligible: false, keywords: ["approved"] },
  chains_rejected: { id: "chains_rejected", label: "Chains Rejected", category: "operations", shortDescription: "Number of candidates rejected this session.", guideDescription: "", routeOrSurface: "/admin/legacy-backfill", tenantOverrideKey: "chains_rejected", isUserFacing: true, isGuideEligible: false, keywords: ["rejected"] },
  help_legacy_backfill: { id: "help_legacy_backfill", label: "Legacy Job Backfill", category: "operations", shortDescription: "How to review and link standalone jobs into rental chains.", guideDescription: "ServiceOS stores rentals as chains — a delivery task, zero or more exchange tasks, and a final pickup task, all linked through `task_chain_links`. Jobs created before the chain architecture existed, or via legacy flows, sit outside any chain as 'standalone jobs'. The Legacy Job Backfill page lets the account owner review those standalone jobs and bring them into the chain architecture one candidate at a time — never automatically, never in bulk without approval.\n\n**How detection works.** The system groups every standalone job in your tenant by (customer, lowercased street, city). Within each group, jobs are sorted by scheduled date and the pattern is inferred: delivery → pickup, delivery → exchange → pickup, delivery-only (no pickup scheduled yet), or orphan (a lone pickup/exchange without a delivery). Each candidate is then given a confidence level. HIGH means the jobs share a customer, street, city, dumpster size, all have scheduled dates, the delivery happened before the pickup, and the gap is 60 days or less — essentially 'this is obviously the same rental'. MEDIUM means the match is likely but something is unusual (different sizes recorded, a large date gap, or missing dates). LOW means the match is weak and you should look closely before approving.\n\n**How approval works.** When you tap Approve on a candidate, the backend runs identity checks first: every job in the candidate must belong to the same tenant AND the same customer, and none may already be in a chain. If any of those fail, the approval is rejected with a clear error and no writes happen. Only after all checks pass does it open a database transaction and create a new `rental_chains` row plus the corresponding `task_chain_links` rows with delivery first, exchanges in the middle, and pickup last. Existing chains are never overwritten — if a job was chained by another request between the pre-check and the transaction, the transaction aborts.\n\n**How rejection works.** When you tap Reject, nothing is written to the jobs or chains — the candidate is recorded on your tenant settings by its sorted job-id fingerprint so the detector won't surface it again. You can always un-reject later by clearing the `legacy_backfill_rejections` blob on `tenants.settings` if a mistake was made.\n\n**What is tracked.** Every approval and rejection is appended to a capped `legacy_backfill_audit` list on your tenant settings with the user id, email, job ids, and timestamp so you can always see who did what. The list is capped at 200 entries to keep the JSONB column small.\n\n**Orphans.** A single pickup or exchange with no matching delivery is flagged as orphan and the Approve button is disabled — those need manual attention (either scheduling a delivery, cancelling the orphan, or researching the data in your source system). They stay visible in the candidate list as a reminder.\n\n**Who can do this.** The page is gated to the account owner role. Dispatchers, admins, and drivers cannot see or approve candidates. The page URL is /admin/legacy-backfill.", routeOrSurface: "/admin/legacy-backfill", tenantOverrideKey: "help_legacy_backfill", isUserFacing: true, isGuideEligible: true, keywords: ["legacy", "backfill", "chain", "help"] },
